Religion events from around the Washington area
Social Issues
Saturday, 8-10:30 a.m.: All-you-can-eat monthly community pancake breakfast featuring oatmeal and regular pancakes. Proceeds benefit the BWC Camping Ministries that operate the West River, Manidokan and Camp Harmison camping and retreat centers and the St. Paul’s Hunger Ministry. St. Paul’s United Methodist Church, 10401 Armory Ave., Kensington. $6.50; $2 for age 11 and younger; $18 family maximum. 301-933-7933.
Saturdays, 8 a.m. to noon: Our Local Bounty farmers market offers Maryland produce, food and jewelry. St. Thomas Episcopal Church, 14300 St. Thomas Church Rd., Upper Marlboro. 301-627-8469.
Saturday, 11 a.m. to 11 p.m.; Sunday, 6, noon to 6 p.m.: Holy Transfiguration Melkite Greek-Catholic Church will host its 22nd annual Middle Eastern Food Festival. The Festival will feature authentic Middle Eastern food, music and dancing, vendors, church tours and other activities. Foods available for purchase. A roasted lamb dinner will take place at 6 p.m. Saturday and all day on Sunday.After the meal, join in the Debkedance. Instructors will teach you how. Or try your hand in the backgammon tournament. For children, a moon bounce, face painting, pony rides, a petting zoo and more. This is a rain-or-shine event. Holy Transfiguration Melkite Greek-Catholic Church, 8501 Lewinsville Rd., McLean. Free admission and parking. 703-734-9566. www.MiddleEasternFoodFestival.com.
Saturdays, 12:30 p.m.: Weekly carillon recital by Edward M. Nassor. Washington National Cathedral, Bishop’s Garden area, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. Free. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Saturday, 1 to 3 p.m.: Historic Pohick Church “First Saturday” tours. The church’s Docent Guild will lead guided tours of the historic Colonial church on the first Saturday of every month. During the Colonial period, Pohick Church was the congregation of many prominent families, including the Washingtons, Masons and Fairfaxes. Golden Dove Gift Shop, located in the historic Vestry House, will be open during tour hours. The Pohick Church, 9301 Richmond Hwy., Lorton. Free. 703-339-6572. www.pohick.org.
Sunday, 8 and 10 a.m.: Washington National Cathedral finishes its summer-only worship schedule. The first service, with Holy Eucharist, Rite 1, remains at 8 a.m. The 9 and 11:15 a.m. services are combined at 10 a.m., with Holy Eucharist, guest musicians and the traditional coffee hour following. Washington National Cathedral, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. Free. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Sunday, 8:30 and 11 a.m.: Now that summer is almost gone, the regular two-service worship schedule returns. Everyone is welcome! Annandale United Methodist Church, 6935 Columbia Pike, Annandale. For information, call 703-256-8330.
Sundays, 8:45 a.m.; Wednesdays, 6 p.m.: Bible study. Calvary Episcopal Church, 509 I St. NE. Free. 202-546-8011.
Sunday, 9 a.m.: Adult Bible study continues on the first and third Sundays. A Bible passage will be read, with questions for discussion following. Various translations will add to the study’s value. Church of the Ascension and St. Agnes, undercroft, 1217 Massachusetts Ave. NW. Free. 202-347-8161.
Sunday, 9 a.m.: A youth group for students in grades six to 12 meets on the first and third Sundays of each month. Members share their thoughts on anything they wish to discuss, including the possibility of community service activities. The Church of the Ascension and St. Agnes, 12th Street atrium, just off the undercroft, 1217 Massachusetts Ave. NW. Free. 202-347-8161.
Sunday, 1 p.m.: Knitting and crocheting workshop. Join fellow needlers to create items for those in need; instruction, needles and yarn provided. Washington National Cathedral, fourth floor of the South Tower, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. Free. Mila Michael, knitting@cathedralcongregation.org. 202-537-6200.
Sunday, 1:30 p.m.: Close-up Tour: Needlepoint. Docents will lead an exploration of some of the 1,500 pieces of needlework in the cathedral and explain the messages they convey. Washington National Cathedral, Front Nave, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. $20; children, seniors, military and students, $16. Reservations are suggested. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Sunday, 7:30 p.m.: YouthCUE concert. The San Antonio-based multidenominational nonprofit organization is dedicated to the advancement of church and school youth choirs across North America. It will perform under the batons of group founder Randy Edwards and André J. Thomas, director of choral activities and professor of choral music education, Florida State University. The program will feature works by well-known composers of classical favorites. Washington National Cathedral, Nave, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. Free. 202-537-6200 or www.nationalcathedral.org.
Most weekdays, 10:30 a.m. and 1:30 p.m.: Behind-the-scenes cathedral tour for ages 11 and older. See gargoyles and stained-glass windows and climb a lot of stairs to view the city from above. Washington National Cathedral, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. $25; children, seniors, students and military, $21. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Mondays, noon: “Brown Bag and Bible.” The Rev. Janice Mynchenberg leads a weekly study of the Gospel of Luke with the help of a commentary by N.T. Wright. Bring your lunch. Georgetown Lutheran Church, 1556 Wisconsin Ave. NW. Free. 202-337-9070 or www.byfaithhopelove.com/GTL.
Mondays, 7 p.m.: Monday night worship services feature a less formal atmosphere in a somewhat smaller setting. Celebration of Communion, with refreshments following. Child care available. Lutheran Church of St. Andrew, 15300 New Hampshire Ave., Silver Spring. info@mystandrew.org. 301-384-4394. www.mystandrew.org.
Mondays, 7 p.m.: Sally Jones leads “A Course in Miracles.” Davies Memorial Unitarian Universalist Church, 7400 Temple Hills Rd., Camp Springs. Free. 301-449-4308. www.dmuuc.org.
Mondays, 7 p.m.: Kirsten Norris leads yoga sessions. Bring a mat. Pilgrim Church United Church of Christ, social hall, 2206 Briggs Rd., Silver Spring. Suggested donation, $5 to $10. The Rev. Jessie Lowry, jessdoerrer@gmail.com. 877-792-8479.
Tuesdays and Thursdays, 9:15 a.m.: Senior Fit, an exercise class for ages 55 and older to build strength, fitness and cardiovascular health. Required physician consent form is available at the information center or by visiting the Web site. Lutheran Church of St. Andrew, 15300 New Hampshire Ave., Silver Spring. Free. Call Marilee at 301-384-4394 or go to www.mystandrew.org.

Tuesday, 12:10 p.m.: Internationally known pianist Magdaline Melkonyan will perform. Church of the Epiphany, 1317 G St. NW. Suggested donation, $10. 202-347-2635, Ext. 20.
Tuesdays, 3:45 p.m.: “Spiritual reflections.” A one-hour, docent-led tour explores stories of faithful action and devotion highlighted in glass and stone. Tours include stories, silence, poetry, prayer and reflective invitations. No tours on holidays or during special events. Washington National Cathedral, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. $15. Questions: pilgrimages@cathedral.org. 202-537-6200 or www.nationalcathedral.org.
Wednesdays, 9:30 to 11 a.m.: Bible study. Three co-conveners will meet for a reading of the gospel for the coming Sunday. A friendly format for reflection and discussion; neither preparation nor regular attendance is required. A healing service and an exploration of the life of the saints follows in the chapel. St. Patrick’s Episcopal Church, 4700 Whitehaven Pky. NW. Free. 202-342-2800.
Wednesdays, 7 to 8:30 p.m.: CancerShare, a faith-based support group for those with cancer, cancer survivors and those who sustain them. Child care is available. Burke United Methodist Church, 6200 Burke Centre Pky., Burke. Free. 703-250-6100. www.burkeumc.org.
Wednesdays, 7 p.m.: Tai chi classes. Certified instructor will teach the movement discipline, which may strengthen mind and body, in advanced and intermediate level classes. Davies Memorial Unitarian Universalist Church 7400 Temple Hills Rd., Camp Springs. Suggested donation, $5. 301-449-4308. www.dmuuc.org.
Wednesday, 7:15 p.m.: Adult Choir Open House. The church choir invites anyone of college age or older to see what the joyful noise is all about as it prepares service music for the 8:30 and 11 a.m. worship services from September through July. Regular rehearsals are Wednesdays at 7:15 p.m. Annandale United Methodist Church, 6935 Columbia Pike, Annandale. Information: Pat Vaughn, music director, pvaughn@annandale-umc.org or 703-256-8330.
Thursdays, 7:30 to 8:30 a.m.: Breakfast Bible study. A reading and discussion of the Bible readings for the upcoming Sunday, according to the Revised Common Lectionary. Open to the public. Sponsored by St. Nicholas Episcopal Church. IHOP, 20009 Century Blvd., Germantown. info@saintnicks.com or 240-631-2800.
Thursdays, 11:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m.: Barnabas Bread Basket Community Meals. Lunch will be served every Thursday. Dinner will be served on the last Thursday of the month from 5 to 7 p.m. First Baptist Church, 9258 Center St., Manassas. Free. 703-368-2958.
Thursdays, 4 p.m.: Bible study. The Worship Center, 99 Adams St., Manassas. Free. 571-283-3252.
Thursday, 6 p.m.: Jazz on the lawn. Sandra Y. Johnson and friends will perform a program of bluesy vocals and instrumental jazz. Dog Tag Cafe will have a pop-up concession on the grounds for all performances, with light fare for purchase. The audience may also bring picnic suppers. On Sept. 17 and 24, Marshall Keys and Cloudburst will perform. Grace Episcopal Church, 1041 Wisconsin Ave. NW. 202-333-7100. $10. www.gracedc.org.
Thursday, 6:30 p.m.: Gargoyle tour. Docents will show slides of the building’s whimsical stone gargoyles and grotesques, followed by an outdoor tour; binoculars and cameras welcome. Washington National Cathedral, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. $15, age 12 and younger $6. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Friday, 12:15 to 1 p.m.: In observance of 9/11, organist John Cannon will perform works by Dietrich Buxtehude, Johannes Brahms and M. Searle Wright, Samuel Barber’s “Adagio for Strings” and Charles Ives’s “Variations on ‘America.’ ” National City Christian Church, 5 Thomas Cir. NW. Free, donations welcome. 202-797-0103. www.nationalcitycc.org.
Sept. 12, 8 a.m.: Women’s Prayer Convocation, hosted by the Women’s Ministry of Bride of Christ Church Ministries. The theme is “Warriors on the Battlefield.” The day will start with breakfast and include lunch. This is a time for healing, cleansing and restoration. Vendors are welcome. Convocation Center, 3500 Enterprise Rd., Mitchellville. $40. Register: www.brideofchristcm.org. E-mail boccm@verizon.net. 301-883-2121.
Sept. 12, noon to 5 p.m.: Unity in the Community, an event designed to connect and serve the people of the community, will provide free health screenings, a car show, a mobile career fair, pony rides, vendors, a barbeque cook-off, a crab feast and more. Arrangements have been made to accommodate individuals from every facet of the community. Union Bethel AME Church, 6810 Floral Park Rd., Brandywine. Free. Reservations: Mrs. Ethel Shepard-Powell, 301-372-1700 or mediationmoon@yahoo.com. www.ubame.org.
Sept. 12, 3:30 to 6 p.m.: 24th Annual Pohick Church Crab Feast, sponsored by the Brotherhood of St Andrew. The menu includes crab, fried fish, steamed shrimp, potato salad, pork barbecue sandwiches, corn on the cob, hush puppies and hot dogs for the kids. Pohick Church, Common Room, 9301 Richmond Hwy., Lorton. $30; ages 12-17, $15; age 11 and younger, free. Tickets: Greg Wilson, gregwilson@remax.net or Jud Bireley, judandnance@gmail.com. 703-339-6572.
Sept. 12, 5:30 to 8 p.m.: “Light the City.” Georgetown’s Unity and Peace program, a community-wide event, will begin at 5:30 p.m. with a Mass at Holy Trinity Catholic Church, 3513 N St. NW, where participants will receive a candle, a map and a list of open houses of worship on the church’s front steps. At 6:30 p.m., Christ Church Georgetown, an Episcopal church, invites everyone to listen to music prepared by its new organist and choirmaster, Tom Smith, and sung by a special quartet of choristers. Christ Church Georgetown, 3116 O St. NW. 202-333-6677. www.christchurchgeorgetown.org. Free.
Sept. 12, 7 p.m.: Howard Gospel Choir will perform a program of gospel favorites. Children are welcome. A reception will follow. First Congregational United Church of Christ, 945 G St. NW. Free. 202-628-4317.
Sept. 12, 7 p.m.: Celebrate the 40th anniversary of the “irregular ordination” of the “Washington Four.” Three of the four female priests ordained July 29, 1974, by four retired bishops will be present. The fourth, Diane Tikell, has died. The Rt. Rev. Barbara Harris will preach at the 11:15 a.m. service. Come at 10 a.m. and be a part of the discussion of this ordination and how the church has changed since 1974. A luncheon will follow. All are welcome. St. Stephen and the Incarnation, an Episcopal Church, 1525 Newton St. NW. 202-232-0900. www.saintstephensdc.org/.


— Compiled by Gerri Marmer
